00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:04.580
&gt;&gt; When you hear the phrase
[inaudible] furniture,

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:09.320
is that a style,
or just a location?

00:57:09.320 --> 00:57:10.900
&gt;&gt; Well, it's really both.

00:57:10.900 --> 00:57:16.470
In mid-19th century, the
furniture industry moves west,

00:57:16.470 --> 00:57:21.540
primarily because being nearer
the source of raw materials,

00:57:21.540 --> 00:57:24.570
which were forests, and the
Midwest, and Grand Rapids,

00:57:24.570 --> 00:57:26.480
is surrounded by forest.

00:57:26.480 --> 00:57:29.580
What also made that
possible was the railroads.

00:57:29.580 --> 00:57:32.310
So that instead of
having to, you know,

00:57:32.310 --> 00:57:35.640
just make furniture locally,
they could ship it all around.

00:57:35.640 --> 00:57:38.260
So Grand Rapids, even
though it's fairly isolated,

00:57:38.260 --> 00:57:40.340
it's connected to
the railroad system,

00:57:40.340 --> 00:57:44.900
and it became proportionally
larger center

00:57:44.900 --> 00:57:47.150
of cabinet making
in the country.

00:57:47.150 --> 00:57:50.760
It wasn't bigger than Chicago,
but Chicago was like ten times

00:57:50.760 --> 00:57:54.190
as big and tons of
population, so Grand Rapids,

00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:57.670
it was really synonymous
with furniture.

00:57:57.670 --> 00:58:01.090
So that's one reason that
the term becomes synonymous

00:58:01.090 --> 00:58:02.390
with furniture.

00:58:02.390 --> 00:58:04.940
And much of the furniture being
made there was mass produced

00:58:04.940 --> 00:58:07.760
furniture, and so it
was sort of ordinary.

00:58:07.760 --> 00:58:11.000
It wasn't the high-end really
expensive stuff, which was found

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:12.780
by the Herr brothers in
New York, or something,

00:58:12.780 --> 00:58:14.610
like they had rich clients.

00:58:14.610 --> 00:58:17.980
This was the mass produced, for
the masses, and so the term,

00:58:17.980 --> 00:58:19.820
Grand Rapids Furniture
gets associated

00:58:19.820 --> 00:58:21.350
with that style of furniture.

00:58:21.350 --> 00:58:23.920
It's mostly in the
Eastlake style,

00:58:23.920 --> 00:58:27.820
and also the revival styles
that you see, so it's both.

00:58:27.820 --> 00:58:30.860
It's a furniture place,
but it connotes that kind

00:58:30.860 --> 00:58:33.340
of mass produced furniture
of late 19th century.

00:58:33.340 --> 00:58:34.640
Yeah.

00:58:34.640 --> 00:58:40.720
&gt;&gt; You said the [inaudible]
examples of Federal,

00:58:40.720 --> 00:58:45.460
would that also be
the same as Georgian,

00:58:45.460 --> 00:58:47.790
or what are the differences
between Federal and Georgian?

00:58:47.790 --> 00:58:51.120
&gt;&gt; Well, in England,
it actually--

00:58:51.120 --> 00:58:53.530
most of the styles
originate in France.

00:58:53.530 --> 00:58:57.270
In terms of the neo-classical
designs, that really,

00:58:57.270 --> 00:59:02.300
you can credit Robert Adams with
that, and sometimes people refer

00:59:02.300 --> 00:59:05.770
to that style as
the Adams style,

00:59:05.770 --> 00:59:09.370
because he was really the
person that generated that.

00:59:10.620 --> 00:59:12.910
Georgian furniture, when you
talk about Georgian furniture,

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:15.270
usually refers to
mid-18th century furniture,

00:59:15.270 --> 00:59:17.380
but there were four George's,

00:59:17.380 --> 00:59:19.130
so if it's George
the Fourth furniture,

00:59:19.130 --> 00:59:28.710
it would be early 19th
century, and same style,

00:59:28.710 --> 00:59:40.840
but you don't usually
see that associated

00:59:40.840 --> 00:59:44.170
with neo-classical furniture.

00:59:44.170 --> 00:59:53.740
It's usually more of the
Chippendale furniture,

00:59:53.740 --> 00:59:55.460
from the mid-18th century.

00:59:55.460 --> 00:59:56.760
That's Georgian furniture.

00:59:56.760 --> 00:59:58.110
And as I said, there
were four George's

00:59:58.110 --> 00:59:59.640
so English furniture uses those
terms for the Georgian style,

00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:00.940
but by the neo-classical period,

01:00:00.940 --> 01:00:02.240
it's often referred
to as [inaudible].

